{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509725","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509725"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:18:47+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:18:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11436"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11436","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11436"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.04,0.31,0.04,0.56]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4069"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103459"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4069","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4069"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11436"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85881"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"6"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1485"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4957"},{"type":"contributions","id":"6130"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7062"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10375"},{"type":"contributions","id":"36748"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103459","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103459"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 75-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with increasing weakness and fatigue. He reports difficulty lifting objects while gardening, which he enjoys. He describes low energy in the mornings, and rarely has the energy to eat much, with his primary meal being tea and toast. He has been sleeping more than usual and has noticed his belt needs to be tightened one hole smaller. He visits his best friend once a week for a cup of tea and a catch up.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn review of systems, he denies chest pain, dyspnoea, palpitations, night sweats, fever, change in bowel patterns, blood in stools, abdominal pain, dysphagia, odynophagia, or dizziness. He reports increased urinary frequency over the last few years.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHis medical history is unremarkable and he does not take any regular medications. His wife died two years ago; she previously managed the household, shopping and cooking. He lives at home with his dog, does not smoke or drink alcohol.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears frail but cheerful and reactive. His pulse rate is 75/min, blood pressure 112/77 mmHg with 10 mm systolic postural change, respiratory rate is normal, SpO2 99% on room air, and temperature is normal. He weighs 56 kg with a height of 175 cm (BMI 18.3 kg/m\u00b2). Neurological examination shows intact power and sensation. Mental state examination reveals no cognitive impairment (MMSE 29/30).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of this presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Addison\u0027s disease","Colorectal cancer","Depression","Type 2 diabetes mellitus","Malnutrition"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with weakness, fatigue, weight loss, and a low BMI of 18.3 kg/m\u00b2, which are classic signs of malnutrition in elderly patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMalnutrition\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely explanation for this presentation. The patient\u0027s dietary intake has clearly declined since his wife\u0027s death, with meals consisting primarily of tea and toast. His social circumstances (widowed, previously dependent on wife for meal preparation) are significant risk factors. His BMI of 18.3 kg/m\u00b2 is borderline underweight, and the weight loss indicated by his belt tightening further supports this diagnosis. Malnutrition in the elderly leads to sarcopenia (loss of muscle mass and strength), which explains his weakness and fatigue. This condition increases risk for frailty, physical disability, poor wound healing, increased hospitalizations, and loss of independence. Management should focus on nutritional assessment, dietary supplementation, and addressing underlying social factors affecting food intake.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAddison\u0027s disease\u003C/strong\u003E can cause fatigue and weight loss but typically presents with additional features such as hyperpigmentation, salt craving, postural hypotension with tachycardia, and gastrointestinal symptoms, which are absent in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColorectal cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is an important consideration in an elderly patient with weight loss. However, the absence of alarm symptoms such as change in bowel habits, blood in stool, abdominal pain, or constitutional symptoms like fever or night sweats makes this less likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDepression\u003C/strong\u003E following bereavement could contribute to his presentation. However, he still enjoys gardening, partakes in social outings, and presents with a reactive affect, making depression less likely as the primary diagnosis. Depression and malnutrition often coexist in elderly patients.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EType 2 diabetes mellitus\u003C/strong\u003E could explain increased urinary frequency but typically doesn\u0027t cause weight loss unless poorly controlled. The patient has no history of diabetes, and his symptoms of weakness and fatigue are better explained by malnutrition.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Malnutrition is common in elderly patients and presents with weakness, fatigue, and weight loss.","Social factors such as bereavement can significantly impact nutritional status in older adults.","Malnutrition contributes to sarcopenia and frailty, increasing risk of disability and loss of independence."],"references":["Ritchie, C., Yukawa, M. (2021). \u0022Geriatric Nutrition: Nutritional issues in older adults, UptoDate. Available from https://www.uptodate.com/contents/geriatric-nutrition-nutritional-issues-in-older-adults","Flanagan D, Fisher T, Murray M, Visvanathan R, Charlton K, Thesing C, Quigley G, Walther K. Managing undernutrition in the elderly: Prevention is better than cure. Australian Family Physician. 2012 Sep;41(9):695-9."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85881"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11436"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"85881","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/85881"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-22T17:52:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-22T17:53:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4069"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103459"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"6","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/6"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc75","name":"Geriatrics","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms